 paradigm shift than those it describes. In Kuhn’s “Structure of Scientific Revolutions” at Fifty, leading social scientists and philosophers explore the origins of Kuhn’s masterwork and its legacy fifty years on. These essays exhume important historical context for Kuhn’s work, critically analyzing its foundations in twentieth-century science, politics, and Kuhn’s own intellectual biography: his experiences as a physics graduate student, his close relationship with psychologists before and after the publication of Structure, and the Cold War framework of terms such as “world view” and “paradigm.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aSciencexHistory. 0aSciencexPhilosophy. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aphilosopher of science, thomas kuhn, scientific revolutions, paradigm shift, 20th century, american, philosophy, philosophical, usa, united states, knowledge, objective criteria, incommensurable, history, psychology, considerations, sociology, development by accumulation, progress, puzzle solving, anomalies, copernican revolution, irrational, humanism.1 aAbbott, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCreager, Angela N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaston, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaston, Lorraine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGalison, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarber, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHacking, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaiser, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReisch, George A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichards, Robert J